[Sanguinarine is an benzophenanthridine alkaloid obtained from
sanguinaria (_Sanguinaria canadensis_) and other species of the same
family, including _Argemone mexicana_ (the common name is Mexican
Poppy). The seeds of the plant when pressed and processed as oils may
concentrate the alkaloids. The seeds are most likely the most toxic
portion of this plant.
Members of _Sanguinaria_ spp have been known to be used medicinally
to treat gingivitis, halitosis, and cough. However, prolonged use or
overdose has been demonstrated to cause stomach pain, diarrhea,
visual changes, paralysis, fainting, and collapse.
The plant is unsafe for use in children and should not be used by
pregnant or lactating women. - Mod.TG]
